450","1400–1476":"1400–1476","1410–1476":"1410–1476","1353–Male":"1353–Deceased","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1469":"1469","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1476":"1476","1353":"1353","1374":"1374","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Shotley, Suffolk, England":"Shotley, Suffolk, England","Shotley, Babergh District, Suffolk, England":"Shotley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Babergh District, Shotley, Suffolk, England":"Shotley, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jenney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Jenny  .","Altered form of German   Jenny  , or perhaps of   Jenne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jenny","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Dietrich, Otto.","Swiss German and Alsatian: from a pet form of <i>Jähn</i>, Swiss German and Alsatian form of the personal name   Johannes   (see   John  ).","English: from a pet form of the Middle English personal name <i>Jen</i> (from <i>Jehan</i>; see   Jean   and   John  )."]}]},{"name":"Margareth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margarethe","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":4,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":77,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margareth Jenney was born in 1378, in Shotley, Suffolk, England, her father, Thomas Jenney, was 25 and her mother, Mary, was 19. She married Augustine de Stratton ESQ in 1399, in Shotley, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1469, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 91, and was buried in Shotley, Suffo